Since it refers to a nonlinear optimization problem in which the derivatives are not known, the Nelder–Mead algorithm was implemented in Julia Language to minimize the loss function (
                           Φ
                        ) represented by Eq. (41) by considering as decision variables the ones presented in Table 3 without the asterisk (*). The Nelder–Mead algorithm is based on the concept of a simplex, which means choosing n+1 initial points in the space of the function to be optimized. By calculating the values of each vertice, it is possible to rank them and calculate the average point neglecting the vertices with higher values. The point with a higher value is then reflected in the direction to the average point e.g. centroid. Then, a series of decisions will be made in order to decrease the area of such simplex through reflection, expansion, contraction, and shrinkage to explore the search space and converge to a zone to the optimal solution [22].
